(890,10840,'article book inproceedings technical reportFigure 2: Class hierarchy of the Multimedia Metadata Layer#7B The multimedia object class groups characteristics common to all raw dataobjects. An important attribute of this class is the unique name used to referto an object #28see also section 9#29. Other attributes of this class include theauthor, the creation date, the person who last modi#0Ced the object, and thedate of last modi#0Ccation.The raw data contentofamultimediaobject is referred to by the mechanismknown as Universal Resource Locators #28U.R.L.s#29. This mechanism stemsfrom the W.W.W. #5BBerners-Lee, et al. 94#5D #5BCailliau 95#5D and indicates boththe protocol to be used to retrieve the object #28e.g. ftp, gopher, http#29 as wellas the location of the object itself #28basically the Internet host and a #0Clepathon that host#29.It is important to emphasise the #0Dexibility of the U.R.L. approach: in fact,we believe this is one of the main contributions of the World-Wide Web.Through U.R.L.s, references can be made to documents accessible over the#0Cle transfer protocol, telnet, gopher, etc., on any computer connected tothe Internet. These documents can also be generated upon request, usingthe Common GatewayInterface #28CGI #5BGleeson, Westaway95#5D#29 mechanism.Moreover, the addressing scheme is easily extensible with new protocols.Our terminology is somewhat unusual in that normally the term multime-dia object refers to a structured composite of several single media. In fact,HOME uses a blackbox approach and doesnt address issues such as e.g.synchronisation between di#0Berent media components of a multimedia object#5BBuford 94#5D.274#7B Biomedical images constitute a subset of the images on our image store#28see section 5.2#29. Currently, this set includes ca. 5900 images, whose speci#0Cccharacteristics #28species, sex, stain, etc.#29 are modelled by this subclass.#7B Another subclass of multimedia objects is the class of bibliographical ref-erence